{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f3bfd974-2968-4738-aa1b-2ce883f33c93","content":"The standard approach is to **wrap them behind an interface** and use dependency injection:\n\n```csharp\npublic interface IFileSystem\n{\n    string ReadAllText(string path);\n    void WriteAllText(string path, string contents);\n    bool DirectoryExists(string path);\n}\n```\n\nCreate a real implementation that delegates to `System.IO`, and inject `IFileSystem` into your classes. In tests, mock it.\n\n**Alternatives:**\n- **`System.IO.Abstractions`** — a popular NuGet package that provides this exact pattern out of the box, with `IFileSystem` and a `MockFileSystem` for tests.\n- **`Microsoft.Extensions.FileProviders`** — lighter weight, read-only abstraction built into .NET.\n\n`System.IO.Abstractions` is the most common choice if you need read/write coverage without rolling your own interface.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"a98f155d-ff33-470d-8bda-06ef9acd8115","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about making file system operations testable in a .NET/C# project. They have `File.WriteAllText`, `File.ReadAllText`, and `Directory.Exists` calls scattered across their code.\n\nThis is a general software engineering question, not a task requiring code changes. I should give concise advice.\n\nThe standard approach is to introduce an abstraction (interface) over the file system operations, then inject that interface. This allows mocking in tests.\n\nLet me give a concise answer.","outputTokens":334,"requestId":"1BDA:22AA1:9A6C49:AE8350:6A03E907"},"id":"5e6712a0-06da-4e49-bf48-2256316070a2","timestamp":"2026-05-13T02:59:30.718Z","parentId":"ed5816fa-32a6-4d26-8871-0d9c60ed53aa"}
